Answer 1.1, Baseline (4p)¶

  • Dense network, at least 3 layers, shaped like a pyramid
    • Last layer: 10 nodes, sigmoid.
    • Loss: categorical cross-entropy. Metric: accuracy
  • No preprocessing, regularization. Get at least 70% accuracy.
  • Explain design decisions. Discuss performance.
    • Does it overfit (large/growing gap between loss and val_loss)?
I started with 3 hidden layers, taking the smallest number of units in each layer until the model starts performing worse, gives the highest val_accuracy. Adding more layers didn't result in a better val_accuracy. Adagrad gives best val_accuracy of all keras optimizers. Learning rate of around 0.02 worked best compared to other values. Higher batch size causes more overfitting, lower batch size causes low val_accuracy. The model has high val_accuracy but is overfitting and has some spikes. (length: 495)

def build_model_1_1():
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Reshape((3072,), input_shape=(32,32,3)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(1200, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(200, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(70, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

    model.compile(optimizer=tensorflow.keras.optimizers.Adagrad(learning_rate=0.02),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

Answer 1.2, Preprocess (2p)¶

  • Convert images to greyscale, other preprocessing optional.
    • Input shape should be (32,32,1)
  • Explain design decisions. Is it better? Why (not)?
    • Color information is likely not so useful for classification. Greyscale makes the network smaller, less parameters to learn, less likely to overfit.
Since we want to convert the images to greyscale, I used the rgb2gray function on those. Furthermore the input shape changed as we now have a single dimension for color. There is a slight increase in the val_accuracy of around 0.5% and also less spikes in the validation loss, so a smoother model. Still quite a lot of overfitting. The slight increase in val_accuracy might be because the color of the images introduces some noise in the images. Color does not add information to numbers. (length: 489)

Answer 1.3, Tune (4p)¶

  • Regularize the model. What works best?
    • Should consider batch normalization, dropout, l1/l2 regularization (or Nesterov)
  • Tune other hyperparameters (e.g. learning rate, batch size,...) as you see fit.
    • At least consider tuning learning rate, ideally also momentum, decay, other optimizers
  • Explain your findings and final design decisions. Discuss the results.
    • Should be better, at least it shouldn't overfit
Values 0.1/0.2 and gradually increasing dropout reduces overfitting. Other dropout values/learning rates give worse results. Smaller Batch size decreases validation accuracy, not much effect when larger. With batch normalization the model converges faster resulting in lower validation accuracy, also with higher learning rate. Combining batch normalization and dropout decreases the val_accuracy. def build_model_1_3():
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Reshape((1024,), input_shape=(32,32,1)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(1200, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.1))
    model.add(layers.Dense(200, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.1))
    model.add(layers.Dense(70, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.1))
    model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    
    model.compile(optimizer=tensorflow.keras.optimizers.Adagrad(learning_rate=0.02),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

Answer 2.1, ConvNet (7p)¶

  • Build a sequential ConvNet, get at least 90% accuracy.
    • Conv2D layers, input shape (32,32,1)
    • Consider using blocks of Conv2D layers with maxpooling in between
    • Use zero-padding in Conv2D layers because the images are small
    • At least one dense hidden layer and dense output layer (sigmoid)
    • Consider adding batch normalization, dropout
    • Consider small dropout rates in beginning, larger dropout rates later in network
    • Consider other optimizers and tuning learning rate, momentum,...
  • Explain what you did and why (800 chars). Is it working well?
    • Should be quite elaborate and sensible
I started with three blocks of two convolutional layers each tweaking different filter/kernel sizes. Filter sizes starting with 32 and doubling each block and (4,4) kernel size give best val_accuracy. Adding one more block increases val_accuracy, more blocks gives no improvement. Max pooling generalises the results of the convolutional layers so feature detection is invariant to scale or orientation changes. This gave 92% accuracy, but is overfitting. Dropout each block with gradual increase reduces the overfitting and increases the val_accuracy. Dropout with gradual increase combined with batch normalization each block gives a val_accuracy of 95.5%. Adagrad optimizers gives best val_accuracy of all keras optimizers. (length: 727)

def build_model_2_1():
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (4, 4), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(32, 32, 1)))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (4, 4), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (4, 4), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (4, 4), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (4, 4), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (4, 4), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(256, (4, 4), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(256, (4, 4), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
    model.add(layers.Flatten())
    model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer=tensorflow.keras.optimizers.Adagrad(learning_rate=0.01),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    
    return model

Answer 2.2, Data Augmentation (3p)¶

  • Augment the preprocessed training data.
    • Use small variations (small shifts up-down, left-right) of flips becasue the images are small
    • Large shifts and rotations distort the image too much
  • Explain what you did and why. Discuss the performance of the model.
better on the middle number using the generator and that there is more data to train on. Other augmentations (rotation range, shear range, zoom range, zca_epsilon) give similar results as 2_1 or even worse results when making large augmentations e.g. large zoom or height shift as this removes too much information or flipping the image makes e.g. a 9 appear like a 6. Answer 3.1, Misclassifications (2p)¶

  • Report the test score (on the held-out test data)
    • Should be similar to score of previous model
  • Plot confusion matrix, discuss which classes are often confused.
    • class 1 and 2 are most often confused
  • Visualize the misclassifications in more depth by focusing on a single class
  • Analyse which kinds of mistakes are made for that class.
    • Should contain some insight (e.g. misclassifications when the numbers are curly or noisy)
Classes 1, 3 and 7 seem to be confused most often, where this is somewhat logical as classes 3 and especially 1 appear much more often in the data than most other classes. The model makes the most mistakes by predicting a 7 as a number 1. This may make sense considering a 7 looks pretty close to a 1, however, it does not happen that much the other way around.  Taking a closer look at a single class ('1'): We mainly see 4 types of errors: - The actual label is wrong (or so it seems) - Image is blurry/noisy such that it is not distinguishable at all - Model makes mistake due to number misclassified as it is similar to another number (e.g. 7 looks like a 1) - Model makes mistake due to there being another number close to the number that should be predicted (length: 764)

The third convolutional layer looks more at certain patterns (e.g. diagonal) of the number. Layers after this learn specific combinations of patterns and more complex abstractions. (length: 379)

Answer 3.3, Class activation map (4p)¶

  • Show a class activation map for your last convolutional layer
  • Superimpose the activation map over the image, or plot side by side
    • Should make sense, detect interesting regions to classify the number
def plot_3_3():
  K.clear_session()
  model_2_2 = load_model_from_file(base_dir, 'model_2_2')

  img_tensor = rgb2gray(X_test)[0]
  img_tensor = np.expand_dims(img_tensor, axis=0) 

  img = np.resize(img_tensor, (32, 32))
  plt.imshow(img, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
  plt.axis('off')
  plt.title('Original image')
  plt.show()

  output = model_2_2.output[:, 0]
  last_conv_layer = model_2_2.get_layer('conv2d_7')
  grads = K.gradients(output, last_conv_layer.output)[0]
  pooled_grads = K.mean(grads, axis=(0, 1, 2))
  iterate = K.function([model_2_2.input], [pooled_grads, last_conv_layer.output[0]])
  pooled_grads_value, conv_layer_output_value = iterate([img_tensor])
  for i in range(last_conv_layer.filters):
      conv_layer_output_value[:, :, i] *= pooled_grads_value[i]

  heatmap = np.mean(conv_layer_output_value, axis=-1)
  heatmap = np.maximum(heatmap, 0)
  heatmap /= np.max(heatmap)
  heatmap = cv2.resize(heatmap, (32,32))
  plt.matshow(heatmap)
  plt.title('Class activation map')
  plt.axis('off')
  plt.show()
  dx, dy = 0.05, 0.05
  x = np.arange(-3.0, 3.0, dx)
  y = np.arange(-3.0, 3.0, dy)
  extent = np.min(x), np.max(x), np.min(y), np.max(y)
  im2 = plt.imshow(img, cmap=plt.cm.gray, interpolation='nearest',
                extent=extent)
    
  im1 = plt.imshow(heatmap, cmap=plt.cm.viridis, alpha=.6, interpolation='bilinear',
                 extent=extent)
  plt.title('Superimposed image')
  plt.axis('off')
  plt.show()

Answer 4.1, Fast feature extraction (5p)¶

  • Import the VGG16 model, pretrained on ImageNet
  • Freeze convolutional base, adds a dense layer
  • Consider unfreezing the last few convolutional layers and evaluate whether that works better
    • Check if they do. It is very likely to help.

    • Should get around 80% accuracy
the number of units in the dense layer performed best above 256. All layers frozen of the convolutional base frozen, gives around 60% val_accuracy, last 2 convolutional layers unfrozen converge around 79%, 3 unfrozen gives 83.5%, and 4 unfrozen gives 87.5%. However, I don't want to unlearn too much (catastrophic forgetting), so I only unfreeze the last block. There is no regularization so the model is overfitting a lot. (length: 424)

def build_model_4_1():
  base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(32,32,3))
  
  x = base_model.output
  x = layers.Flatten()(x)
  x = layers.Dense(300, activation='relu')(x)
  predictions = layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax')(x)

  model = tensorflow.keras.Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=predictions)

  for layer in base_model.layers[:-4]:
      layer.trainable = False

  model.compile(optimizer=tensorflow.keras.optimizers.Adagrad(learning_rate=0.01),
                    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                    metrics=['accuracy'])
  
  return model

def store_embeddings():
  """ Stores all necessary embeddings to file
  """
  model = load_model_from_file(base_dir, 'model_4_1', extension='.h5')
  base_model = tensorflow.keras.Model(inputs=model.input, outputs=model.get_layer('block5_pool').output)
  embedding_X_train = base_model.predict(X_train)
  embedding_X_val = base_model.predict(X_val)
  embedding_X_test = base_model.predict(X_test)

  store_embedding(embedding_X_train, 'training')
  store_embedding(embedding_X_val, 'validation')
  store_embedding(embedding_X_test, 'test')

def evaluation_4_2(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
  """ Runs 'evaluate_pipeline' with embedded versions of the input data 
  and returns the accuracy.
  """
  if not (os.path.isfile(base_dir + 'training_embedding.p') and os.path.isfile(base_dir + 'test_embedding.p')):
    store_embeddings()


  test_embedding = load_embedding('test')
  train_embedding = load_embedding('training')
  val_embedding = load_embedding('validation')


  test_embedding = np.reshape(test_embedding, (len(X_test), 512))
  train_embedding = np.reshape(train_embedding, (len(X_train), 512))
  val_embedding = np.reshape(val_embedding, (len(X_val), 512))
  y_train = [(np.argmax(entry)+1)%10 for entry in y_train]
  y_test = [(np.argmax(entry)+1)%10 for entry in y_test]

  return evaluate_pipeline(generate_pipeline(), train_embedding, y_train, test_embedding, y_test)
